description:
My team at Amazon is looking to hire a software engineer. Come build the next generation of robotics software with us!
We are looking for candidates with a background in robotics, RT/embedded development or RPC communication. Most development will be in C++. Experience with ROS or DDS is desired.
Message me for details!


R&D Engineer in robotics, I am a C++ expert (among the 4% top most active coder as of June 2013 on GitHub.com[1]) and particularly interested by humanoid robotics. I have extensive experience on robot control, motion planning and vision for humanoid robots.

I have been working in different high-tech start-up (Gostai, now part of Aldebaran Robotics) and research laboratories (iLab at USC, LRDE at EPITA) around the world (France, USA, Japan). These past experiences gave me a strong background in both research and engineering.

I am dedicated to enhancing robotics community better software and as part of this effort I am a Debian contributor and maintain a couple of robotics software packages on various platforms. I am also a ROS expert (the most popular open-source robotics development platform) and contributor.

I have been given the opportunity to think of robotics software problem from the research idea up to delivering an "industry grade" implementation.

I also led during 5 years a non-profit organization aiming at providing support and information for non-professional video game development (a.k.a. "Indie Games").

Strong engineering skills in C++, Python, Linux and various open source tools.
Applied mathematics and physics.

description:
Software engineer. I haven't updated this in years, so take it with a grain of salt. ---

My career started when I was 12. I simultaneously started learning C++ and HTML, and this event foreshadowed the rest of my career up to this date: balancing the lowest-level and the highest-level code I can get my hands on. Without knowing any Computer Science theory, I wrote an interpreter for a minimalist C-like language using C when I was 14, and I was known as a "JavaScript guru" from age 15-17. 
At age 16, in 2006, I formed Cortex Creations. I worked with some great people and employed a great friend full-time, Joshua Diaz, for 2.5 years. This was a great period of learning for me, as it taught me that it takes more than just technical skill to produce a great product. 
In mid-2008, at the ripe age of 18, I had a mid-career existential crisis and decided to take a break from programming. I spent more time on music, picking up accordion and electronic music and spent more time practicing violin. I also discovered tea, biking, and started a comic series.
The break only lasted a year. By 2009 my interests had diversified. My relationship with Pearson Book Publishing began in 2009; since then I've reviewed several book proposals and reviewed technical accuracy of 2 books currently on the market. I worked on the web team for IceCube, the neutrino physics observatory, at the Madison headquarters during summer 2010. I toyed with Twitter and Safari Extensions, and was featured on Apple's Extension Gallery for a while.

Since 2011 I've been involved at 2 startups, one which was acquired by Yahoo, where I worked for two years. After that I switched gears and have been at a GPS hardware startup, Swift Navigation, since then.

Apple since August 2017.

description:
I am currently working on building adversarial machine learning/ AI applications at Microsoft to empower organizations to secure ML assets at scale.

Before Microsoft, I worked in Quant/Data science team at Morningstar. I primarily worked on building machine learning applications (Risk Models) from scratch using distributed frameworks such as Apache Spark, Python, HDFS, and AWS cloud services to estimate the returns and risks in an investors portfolio. My experience includes, optimized ETL production jobs and model build jobs by leveraging Spark in-built and vectorized UDF functions; This resulted in a massive reduction of execution time while running on AWS EMR cluster. Also, I was involved in architecting and building recommendation models to proactively suggest Morningstar data points that help users to screen funds, ETFs, Stocks etc., so clients can make informed decisions. In addition, I built AWS IAC tools to migration on-premise services to the AWS cloud using cloud formation and Terraform. Automated CICD pipelines using AWS services. Implemented highly scalable, reliable, and cost-effective architectural patterns using  AWS services. I am a certified AWS solutions architect Associate. 

 I graduated from Purdue School of science, Indianapolis majored in computer science. My Master's research includes Data Mining, Large Scale Machine Learning. My thesis was based on Graph Mining.  In my thesis, I proposed and implemented the enumeration of k-cliques in large-scale real-world graphs using distributed framework called Apache Spark. In addition, I also worked as a Research Assistant which involved building classification and regression models using python.

I also interned at Pinnacle Solutions Inc,  as a Data Scientist. My work at Pinnacle includes building and deploying predictive modeling techniques using different classification techniques like SVM, LR using PySpark and compared with SAS Eminer and AWS ML.

description:
Computer Science Graduate Student with a can-do attitude, phenomenal time management skills, and a strong user focus actively looking for a role where I may be able to use my well-honed skills to develop state-of-the-art scalable software solutions.

That's a brief of who I am and what I am looking for!

A bit deeper about myself:
I strive to be an Algorithm Engineer. This sprouted because I am mainly interested in how things work the way they work. For example: If you give me an algorithm and say that this works for a particular problem- my first question would be how does it work? What's the idea behind it? Why not some other way? What are the pros and cons of it? What was the approach that is worse than this? 
This thinking made to be successful as a programmer till now and enhanced my interest in Algorithms.

Besides, this interest in reasoning made me to develop curiosity in understanding how Machine Learning and Deep learning models actually work. What is the model learning at each step? I want to explore this Blackbox which I think would pave a way to make the Deep learning models better.

Apart from being a Computer Science Engineer, I have an immense interest in Neuroscience and would love to learn and talk about it. I am also a philanthropist who likes to participate in volunteer activities including teaching, taking care of homeless people, feeding animals and treating dogs.

headline:
As a kid, I spent hours lying on the ground outside studying ants. I had many questions: How do they follow the other ants? Why do they walk in straight lines? How do they find food? My determined curiosity and laser focus led to hours of examination. I perceived patterns, intuited theories, and performed experiments to verify my ideas. And I have been wondering about the world ever since.

Currently, I am a data scientist providing analytic support for Minecraft at Microsoft. I have 10 years of experience in computational science and scientific data analysis through research during my graduate school and postdoctoral work. My tenacious curiosity and technical skills make me an excellent data detective.

Besides my quantitative skills, I also love the challenge of comm've presented 12 conference posters, given 8 technical lectures, and published 5 peer-reviewed articles.

headline:
As Director of the Google Customer Experience Laboratory, I lead a horizontal organization tasked with understanding Google's customers, and their experiences within and across the Google product ecosystem.  Our findings provide business leadership with actionable insights to shape product strategy, investment, and direction, with the ultimate goal of giving our customers the best experience possible.

In my prior role as Chief Data Science Officer at Honeywell, I shaped the technology and business approach to data science, data management, and data engineering for the Connected Enterprises business and for the Corporation. In partnership with business and analytics leaders across the enterprise, we enabled and advanced IoT services and products that leverage data, analytics, and artificial intelligence, creating massive value for our customers. 

Before moving to Honeywell, I was Vice President of Data Science at Capital One, where I moved the needle around adoption of a data science culture, and accelerated advanced analytics and AI into the heavily regulated financial services environment.  Prior to Capital One, I was Vice President of Data Science Services at GE Digital where I developed the Company's data science talent model, culture and capability, established a new data science services business model spanning the GE verticals such as Healthcare, Aviation and Oil & Gas, and enabled Analytics as a Service (AaaS) via Predix, GE's big data and analytics software platform. 

As a classically trained electrical, biomedical, and systems engineer, I have leveraged my experience in startup and Fortune 100 environments to launch products and services into the market - from R&D to NPI, across hardware, software, biomedical and point-of-care systems, to digital pathology and financial services solutions requiring FDA, NRC, FAA, OCC and other regulatory approval and compliance.

From academia through present day, my career focus has been on enabling business and societal impact at scale - through products, services, and actionable insights from data.

headline:
As part of my recently concluded internship at Microsoft, I analyzed BERT (the Deep Bidirectional Transformer for Language Understanding) for the purpose of integrating it into the Automated Machine learning pipelines. I evaluated how to best leverage and tune the "fine-tuning" process of BERT in order to use it as a transformer for downstream classification tasks. We employ a simple Bag of Words model as well as other DNN based architectures for comparisons from the perspective of both metrics (like accuracy) as well as efficiency (training time).
Areas of learning include Deep Neural Networks based Language Models, classical NLP, Parallel Processing via multiple GPUs, Pytorch based model implementation.

I have also successfully completed graduate courses like Statistical Machine Learning, Applied Statistics and Experimental Design, Introduction to Statistics and Probability, Information Visualization, and Database Management at UW with a cumulative GPA of 3.88. 

I've been a Research Assistant at the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation, where I worked on estimating the burden of disease averted by personal health care in the US, where burden is measured by disability-adjusted-life-years and personal health care by the healthcare quality and access index.

I previously worked in Algorithmic Trading at Goldman Sachs, for 5 years where I analyzed market data, in the form of time series data, to calibrate signals for trading algorithms and worked on numerous regression problems to determine the optimal tolerance bands for trading. I've played a multitude of roles, from quantitative research on volume profiles to being a lead developer for highly time sensitive trading algorithms in an event-driven programming language. jobDescription2:
I'm now leading an upstart Data Science team in our Worldwide Learning team at Microsoft.  Our challenge is how to apply data science methods and analytics to truly understand the impact of our learning offerings for Microsoft employees, our customers, and our partners.  Thus far, here are some examples of what we've done.
- Employee skilling - we've built ways to use existing internal data sets to really measure the impact of our learning offerings on MS employees.  This has allowed us to understand both behaviorally where learners are demonstrating skills as well as ROI and business impact for key programs.
-  Manager/Coaching - we built a model leveraging calendar data to reflect manger "intensity" relative to time between a manager and their directs to see how our Coaching training created space and autonomy for our employees.
-  Certification planning - we've built a data-driven way to use in-market skills and job data to better understand the need and projections in considering new learning and certifications.
-  Feedback 360 - we've designed a way to integrate all of the different messages we get from our learners into an integrated an usable solution.  We'll be building this in the upcoming year and layering natural language on top of it to really reason across this disparate data.
-  Certification Journey analysis - we've built a model to represent the complete certification journey of any MS certified learner in the past 12 years.  This allows us to build correct paths for learners for new certifications as well as better author marketing and outreach content to get learners to the right destination.
-  Linkedin Analytics - we've partnered closely with our peer teams at LinkedIn to more formally exchange data to use in-market skills as the way to measure our learning business.

description:
1. Deep Learning Project (Image Authentication) 

Created a facial image authenticator to help social media users identify manipulated profile pictures. A modified transfer learning model (ResNet50) was used to train 100,000 color JPEG images which were preprocessed from mp4 videos to resized (640, 480, 3) color images using OpenCV. The output from the pre-trained model is passed into a dense layer with 10 neurons with ReLu activation function and finally passed into a dense layer of a single output neuron with a sigmoid function which outputs 1 (if manipulated) and 0 (if real). The current accuracy on the training and evaluation datasets is 55% and 52% respectively. This project is currently on hold until further collection of more data and AWS purchasing power for hyperparameter modeling tuning. 

2. Statistical and Machine Learning Projects

- Entertainment recommendation for soccer fans based on European soccer data (2008-2016, 8 seasons, 11 leagues) using statistical exploration, bootstrapping and hypothesis testing. 
- Performed exploratory data analysis, feature engineering and extracted actionable insights from historical housing data using xgboost regressor.
- Forecasted the price of monthly pet insurance premium using a univariate time-series model (SARIMAX).

headline:
I love building teams and making great data products. I hate selling myself. So here's a handful of things about me and my work. In. Out. No one gets hurt. 

1) I've built data science solutions for two of the largest and ubiquitous insurance brands in the US. I've dug deep into the data to find answers to ambiguous questions and worked with stakeholders to turn those insights into product improvements. 

2) I love data science. But I love developing data scientists more. There's nothing more satisfyingly than watching those you've invested in grow and succeed. 

3) My first job was to collect carts for a big box retailer at age 16. In the very rainy northwest. That job convinced me that I absolutely HAD to go to college because I was not about that life.

4) I'm sort of obsessed with agile as it applies to data science. I helped to kick start adoption of agile in my role as a supervisor of an analytics team at GEICO and I've been applying it and learning lessons ever since. I think ultimately agile is about creating relationships of trust amongst everyone involved in a work stream, up, down, and sideways and pushing decisions to the people with the most information. When that's done right, you'll do some of the best work of your life.

headline:
After more than 20 years of experience working  on data driven solutions to USG and Industry enterprise security problems, I'm convinced  of certain things:

1. Attackers are going to penetrate perimeter defenses. Yet, only the most mature security operations have visibility and understand their normal enterprise behavior, let alone those of an attacker.

2. Statistical methods are under-utilized for attack detection.  There is huge promise in identifying attack-consistent events that are also rare with respect to a historic, predictive model.  A good understanding of the underlying model assumptions, combined with security domain knowledge, is critical to the proper application of statistical or machine learning approaches.

3. Attacks do not happen in isolation on a single endpoint. Instead, they are exhibited across multiple endpoints, and in the communications between these endpoints. This leads to questions about local, connected subgraphs, within the larger network graph.

4. Networks create rare events continuously! As such, I focus on not only quantifying rarity, but security-relevant rarity.

5. Context is everything. Telling the forensic story to the analyst, as much as possible with the data available, is the difference between rapid detection of only true breaches and foundering in a sea of false positives.
